sentences: Jean Redpath MBE (28 April 1937 – 21 August 2014) was a Scottish folk singer, educator and musician.
In March 1961, at the age of 24, she arrived in the United States with just eleven dollars in her pocket.
In 1963, following a concert performance, she signed up with Elektra Records.
In 1975, she switched to the Philo label.
From 1972 to 1976, Redpath was artist-in-residence at Wesleyan University in Middletown, Connecticut.
In 1976, Redpath embarked on a project to record all the songs of Robert Burns, some being folk songs, some Burns's own compositions, and most a mixture of the two.
In 1986, she recorded Lady Nairne, a collection of songs written by Scottish women.
Between 1974 and 1987, Redpath appeared regularly on Garrison Keillor's "A Prairie Home Companion" APM radio show.
She also appeared on Robert J. Lurtsema's "Morning pro musica" broadcast from WGBH in Boston.
In 1977, Royal Jubilee Year, Redpath appeared at a royal banquet at Edinburgh Castle for Queen Elizabeth II.
In 1977, Royal Jubilee Year, Redpath appeared at a royal banquet at Edinburgh Castle for Queen Elizabeth II.
Starting in 1979, Redpath was a lecturer at the University of Stirling, Scotland, with occasional trips to teach at Wesleyan University.
She gave courses for ten years  in Scottish Song at the Heritage of Scotland Summer School at the University of Stirling.
She gave courses for ten years  in Scottish Song at the Heritage of Scotland Summer School at the University of Stirling.
She was awarded the MBE in 1987, as well as being named a Kentucky colonel by the Governor of Kentucky.

Redpath also received honorary doctorates from the Royal Conservatoire of Scotland, University of Stirling and the University of St Andrews, and was inducted into the Scottish Traditional Music Hall of Fame in 2008.
In 1996, she launched the Burns International Festival.
In 2009, Redpath made an appearance on the Late Show with David Letterman, singing "Some Kind of Love" by the late John Stewart of the Kingston Trio.
In 2011, she returned to her alma mater to become artist-in-residence at the University of Edinburgh’s Department of Celtic and Scottish Studies.
Redpath died from cancer on 21 August 2014 at a hospice in Tucson, Arizona.
